What is R?

R is an open source language and environment for statistical computing and graphics.

It is based on S, which was a language developed by Bell Laboratories in the 1970s.

There is an R Development Core Team who write the R source code, the R Foundation who control the design and evolution of base R, and the R Project, which features thousands of international contributors. UseRs develop their own collection of funcitons called "packages", which can be publicly distributed on the Comprehensive R Archive Network (CRAN). That's where we will get many of our functions!

Why R?

It's free and will always be free and open source.

Community:

  • Ask questions: http://stackexchange.com
    • R questions: http://stackoverflow.com/
    • General statistics: http://stats.stackexchange.com/
  • R Bloggers: r-bloggers.com
  • DataCamp: datacamp.com
  • Examples and tips: statmethods.net
  • Search R specific sites: rseek.org
  • Cheat sheets: onepager.togaware.com

Why R?…

Designed for statistical operations, so almost all statistical methods are available, especially the very new ones!

Beautiful graphics, analysis, text mining, interactive visualizations, and even slide presentations (like this one)!

Installing R

  1. Go to the website: https://www.r-project.org/
  2. Click Download R: https://cran.r-project.org/mirrors.html
  3. Select your mirror (server): University of Toronto: http://cran.utstat.utoronto.ca/
  4. Download R for appropriate platform:
  • R 3.3.1 binary for Mac OS X 10.9 (Mavericks)
  • Base -> R 3.3.1 for Windows
  • Linux (you can figure it out if you are running linux)

R

This is R

If you have a solid coding background, R may be enough for you. If you are more comfortable with GUI (graphic user interfaces), RStudio is a better option.

Installing RStudio

  1. Go to the website: https://www.rstudio.com/
  2. Click "Download R Studio"
  3. Open Source Edition (that means it's FREE!)
  4. Download R Studio Desktop: https://www.rstudio.com/products/rstudio/download/

  • Mine is OS X 10.6 -> note which version you have because some code and packages only work with certain versions.

  • For more installation instructions you can visit: https://github.com/MHS-R/R-Guide/wiki/Installing-R

The RStudio Console

We type code in the Script Editor, and the output goes to the Console. Any variables or datasets are saved in the R Workspace, which you can check by clicking the Environment and History tabs.

Getting Started

To write a new R script, go to File and select New File then R Script.

If you already have a file saved that you want to open, click File then Open File.

.R files are text files, so you can edit them in any text editor across platforms.

Base R

RStudio comes with a "base" library that has many functions, like addition and division, that will return output:

4+4
## [1] 8

Install Non-Base Libraries

For functions that are not in the base program, we need to install packages. Go to the "Packages" tab and click "Install". Choose "Repository (CRAN)" from the drop-down menu, then type the name of the package you want into the search bar and click "Install". Install all dependencies.

You will be able to scroll through your packages to see which ones are selected at any given time.

Non-CRAN Packages

We can install beta packages not on CRAN by downloading them from the web (https://github.com/trending?l=R), select "Install from Package Archive File".

  • There will be less support in the communities for beta packages, but often the developers will answer your questions if you email them directly.

Let's get started!

Type Data into Variables

# We create `variables` by typing them into the `Script Editor`.
x <- c(1,2,3,4,5)
# Call x by clicking **Run** or by pressing **command** and **return**.  
x
## [1] 1 2 3 4 5

The variable x is saved in the R Workspace and will exist until it is deleted (or R is restarted). You can check the contents of the Workspace with the ls() function.

ls()
## [1] "x"

Basic arithmetic

What if you want to use R to calculate a grade for a student you TA. Say the student got 18/25 on the first test, 20/25 on the second test, and 22/25 on the third test. They want to know what they need on the final /25 to get an A (85%) in the course.

y <- (18+20+22) # or y <- c(18,20,22) ; sum(y) 
y
## [1] 60
85-y
## [1] 25

You can tell the student that they will need to get a perfect score on the final to get that coveted 85%

Addition + Subtraction - Multiplication * Division /

1+1 
## [1] 2
2-1
## [1] 1
3*2
## [1] 6
4/2
## [1] 2

PEDMAS

R will even figure out the order of operations for you!

1+2*3/4
## [1] 2.5

And you can do arithmetic to vectors

z <- x^2
z
## [1]  1  4  9 16 25

Adding a constant

You can add a constant to a vector easily by adding the constant 5 to the variable x. Remember x <- c(1,2,3,4,5)

x
## [1] 1 2 3 4 5
x+5
## [1]  6  7  8  9 10

QUICK SAVE!

Sometimes R and RStudio crash, so make sure you save frequently.

You can save by pressing command and s or by clicking File then Save

Creating vectors

Vectors are a sequence of data of the same numerical type. Remember Nominal, Ordinal, Interval, Ratio? Data in a vector must all be of the same kind.

Nominal <- c("Arlie", "Matthew", "Huxley", "Lulu", "Maya")   
# with actual data use factor()
Ordinal <- c("First", "Second", "Third", "Fourth", "Fifth")  
# with actual data use ordered()
Interval <- c(1, 1.5, 2, 5, 5.5, 7)
Ratio <- c(0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5)

This is not a vector!

wrong <- c("Arlie", 1, 2.111111111111119, "Blue")

Storing Data as a Matrix

We can combine vectors of the same size and data type into a matrix.

matrix <- matrix(data=c(-5,2,7,1,2,3,3,6,-4), 
                 nrow=3, ncol=3)
matrix
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]   -5    1    3
## [2,]    2    2    6
## [3,]    7    3   -4

Binding columns and rows

Add columns and rows to a matrix using rbind and cbind

w <- c(1,2,3)
rbind(matrix,w)
##   [,1] [,2] [,3]
##     -5    1    3
##      2    2    6
##      7    3   -4
## w    1    2    3
cbind(matrix,w)
##              w
## [1,] -5 1  3 1
## [2,]  2 2  6 2
## [3,]  7 3 -4 3

Binding columns and rows into a data frame

We can combine vectors of the same size but different data types into a data frame.

n <- c(2, 3, 5) 
s <- c("aa", "bb", "cc") 
b <- c(TRUE, FALSE, TRUE) 
dataframe <- data.frame(n, s, b)       
dataframe
##   n  s     b
## 1 2 aa  TRUE
## 2 3 bb FALSE
## 3 5 cc  TRUE

Naming columns and rows of a matrix

colnames(matrix) <- c("X","Y","Z")
matrix
##       X Y  Z
## [1,] -5 1  3
## [2,]  2 2  6
## [3,]  7 3 -4
rownames(matrix) <- c("A","B","C")
matrix
##    X Y  Z
## A -5 1  3
## B  2 2  6
## C  7 3 -4

Your own data

You probably have your own datasets that you need to run though. You'll want to save them as .csv in Excel.

mydata <- read.csv("filename.csv")
mydata

If you've included a row of variable names in the dataset, you'll want to add this:

mydata <- read.csv("filename.csv", header=TRUE)

Or you can go to Environment then Import Dataset to find it from your computer.

Working Directory

A working directory is the folder where R Studio saves your R script and gets the data. By default, R will set the working directory to your user directory. You might want to work in a different folder. To do this, you can go Files then More then Set Working Directory. Make sure all your data files are in the same directory you've saved your R script. If you move them later, your script might not work.

HELP!

I got an Error! Or I forgot what that function was called. What do I do now? You can use the R Studio Help tab to search for key words. Or you can use ? and ?? in the R Script Editor.

? will search for an exact match to what you type in any loaded packages

?? will search for a similar match across all packages installed locally

?t.test
?ttest
## No documentation for 'ttest' in specified packages and libraries:
## you could try '??ttest'
??ttest
